by CBG-Palisade » Sat Apr 17, 2021 10:24 am

The Mizian view of democracy's role in society is best described as "bottom down"; that is, at a community level individual participation in government is important and even essential, but that at a higher level the monarch should retain a good deal of executive power. This has led to an interesting situation where they've devolved a significant portion of day-to-day management to citizens but retain their monarchy- similar, I find it interesting to point out, to a feudalistic hands-off approach.

ColBureau developed as a response to society's aversion to liberalism and right wing libertarianism, branded as culprits of the climate collapse, born from the mass consumerism and rampant egoism of an era. ColBureau was thus created as a system that would make sure the individuals would have barriers (and paperwork) separating their ill-advised ambitions from the disastrous consequences they could bring. However, in many cases, the bureaucracy spiraled our of control, acquiring life of it's own. The system no longer functioned for the People, not even for it's creators or the common good. Now it functioned because it couldn't stop. It mustn't stop.

by Liagolas » Mon Apr 19, 2021 7:53 pm

So, Sophia in England. Oh, it's a narrative Factbook with a framing device, that's fun. I've tried that, though I'm realizing academic press book is a pretty dry framing device. A video game with saves, loads, and a menu screen seems a lot more fun.

1800s England seems about like what you'd expect. Trains for transport, school for nobles. But Sophia is very forward-thinking. She doesn't seem to have any prejudices against foreigners. If she was going to dislike Sakura, it was over flashiness not nationality. And if the images are to be taken at face value, she cuts some daring skirt lengths for the era.

Most of the story remains WIP so far, but story 3 hints at something funny that's also mentioned in the signature. The math genius- Vivian?- can't do arithmetic? Wonder what that means.


Okay, so. Sternenstaat. One thing I learned is that the Staat is diarchic and has managed to combine feudalist sensibilities with populist autocracy. Combing power from the people with power from the center, you don't often see that. The kaiser is "embodiment of the state" while the kanzler is "prime representative." So it seems like originally at least the kaiser held the real keys of power, but over time reforms have empowered the kanzler more and more, hence both a feudal king in the kaiser and a populist autocrat in the kanzler. I'm assuming the kanzler is somehow democratically elected? And that's why the position is called populist. But I can't see it actually said anywhere in the National Factbook that there are elections so I could've gotten it wrong.
